  "prompt": "What are some kind words to say to a friend with a sick parent?",
  "response": "When a friend has a sick parent, knowing what to say can be difficult. The key is to offer genuine support and understanding without minimizing their experience. Here are some kind words you can say:\n\n**Expressing Empathy and Understanding:**\n\n*   \"I'm so sorry to hear about your mom/dad. That must be incredibly difficult.\"\n*   \"I can only imagine how challenging this must be for you and your family.\"\n*   \"My heart goes out to you and your parent.\"\n*   \"I'm thinking of you and your family during this tough time.\"\n*   \"This must be so hard. It's okay to not be okay.\"\n\n**Offering Practical Support:**\n\n*   \"Is there anything I can do to help?  Even something small like bringing over a meal, running errands, or just being someone to listen.\"\n*   \"Let me know if you need anything at all. No matter how big or small, I'm here for you.\"\n*   \"Would you like me to help with [specific task]?\" (e.g., \"Would you like me to walk your dog this week?\" or \"Can I pick up groceries for you?\")\n*   \"I'm happy to just sit and listen if you need to vent. No pressure to talk if you don't want to.\"\n*   \"If you need a break, I'm happy to [offer a specific form of respite, e.g., stay with your parent for an hour].\"\n\n**Validating their Feelings:**\n\n*   \"It's understandable that you're feeling [sad/stressed/overwhelmed/etc.].\"\n*   \"Your feelings are valid. Don't feel like you need to be strong all the time.\"\n*   \"It's okay to grieve/worry/be scared.\"\n*   \"There's no right or wrong way to feel in this situation.\"\n\n**Offering Hope and Positive Thoughts (Use with Caution):**\n\n*   \"I'm sending positive thoughts/prayers your way.\" (Only if you know your friend is receptive to this.)\n*   \"I'm hoping for the best possible outcome for your parent.\"\n*   \"I'm sending strength and healing vibes to your family.\"\n\n**Things to AVOID Saying:**\n\n*   \"I know how you feel.\" (Unless you've been in a very similar situation, this can minimize their experience.)\n*   \"Everything happens for a reason.\" (This can be insensitive and unhelpful.)\n*   \"At least they had a good life.\" (This is dismissive of their current pain.)\n*   Giving unsolicited medical advice.\n*   Changing the subject or focusing on your own problems.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Be genuine:** Don't say anything you don't mean.\n*   **Be specific:**  Instead of a general \"Let me know if you need anything,\" offer a specific task.\n*   **Listen more than you talk:**  Let your friend share their feelings and experiences without interruption or judgment.\n*   **Follow through:** If you offer help, be sure to follow through on your offer.\n*   **Check in regularly:**  Even a simple \"Thinking of you today\" text can make a big difference.\n*   **Respect their boundaries:** Understand if they need space or don't want to talk about it.\n*   **Don't take it personally** if they are withdrawn or short with you. They are likely under a lot of stress.\n\nUltimately, the best thing you can do is be a supportive and understanding friend. Let your friend know you're there for them, and be willing to listen without judgment. Your presence and support will mean more than any perfect words you can say.\n",
